<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I tend to argue with other Christians, too, on certain points. Ever been to the Kjos Ministries? <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://crossroad.to">crossroad.to</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> Ugggh...they drive me up a wall. Go there, they'll drive you up a wall, too, I gurantee it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Heheh!! Okay, I’ll check it out  &amp; let you know if I’m still (relatively) sane afterwards .<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/emoticons_classic/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I have great respect for someone who does not believe and will argue the point who ACTUALLY KNOWS what the Bible says and what they are talking about. Thank you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, I guess I have a kinda obsessive personality, which has its up sides too.. if I get interested in or espec. *believe* in  something, then I want to know as much as poss about it, plus it is genuinely interesting finding out about the background to Christianity (&amp; other religions).. in other words, if the Bible isn’t ‘divinely inspired’ (which obviously I believe it wasn’t) then who wrote it and why, where did it come from? I like finding out about stuff like that (the Qumran Scrolls, the ‘forgotten’ Gospels that got junked by the Romans when the New Testament was formalised, etc).. it’s interesting.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I believe in the goodness of God (though, yes, I question it sometimes), and I follow him, so, I suppose that makes me evil? Pheh, so many people say that I have &quot;a good heart&quot;. I'm rather hard pressed to find people who will call me evil.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Nope, ofcourse  I’m  not saying YOU are evil.. I’m saying that (to me) the God decribed in the Bible *is* evil (or malign, whatever).. ultimately, I can’t *know* whether the Christian God or any other deity exists, my opposition to Christianity also lies in the fact that I don’t feel the God of the OT to be worthy of any respect, let alone worship, if He exists.. so I guess I’m very Deeply opposed to Christianity in that sense, beyond simply ‘non belief’.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Actually, I was thinking of posting a topic like this on the TRHQ (Team Rocket Headquarters...yes, it's a Pokemon board, but there are a lot of philosophical people there, surprisingly) for some thoughts on this issue, for help on a comic I'm doing.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sounds a good idea!  It’s interesting posting topics about issues like these on boards not about religion etc .. I posted a topic about Satanism on the off topic section of a message board about a Vietnam War film.. which was really interesting &amp; got a really discussion going with lots of twists &amp; turns (though I kinda think people missed the point of what I was saying, which was about *labels*)<br>
<br>
Anyway, if you’d like to see how it went, you can find the topic here:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.weweresoldiersfilm.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=2000&start=0">www.weweresoldiersfilm.co...00&start=0</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I've been thinking about some themage in this post apocalyptic epic fantasy comic that I'm drawing, &quot;Paper Eagles&quot;... I would like a scene somewhere in the comic where a Feanari warrior has my main character at swordpoint and is talking about his goddess demanding that he kill him, to which my main character replies something along the lines of &quot;Is your goddess really that afraid of me? If she wants me dead, can't she do it herself?&quot; or something like that. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Hmmm, have you ever read any Anne Rice? One of the thngs I love about her writing is the way she weaves religious themes into so much of it, her background is as a catholic &amp; I guess that works its way into a lot of her work..<br>
<br>
In Queen of the Damned (the book, NOT the dreadful sounding travesty of a film) she describes the origins of the vampires, and goes way back to Egypt 1000s of years ago.. the Queen herself (Akasha) is obsessed with finding some sort of (redemptive?) religious ‘truth’.. she desperately needs to find a sorcer(ess) who’s for real, spirits that won’t turn out to be just shadows, she NEEDS faith.. in the end, she gets totally disillusioned, but fate (or a powerful spirit) intervenes.. she’s stabbed to ‘death’ along with her husband, but @ that point this spirit collects itself around her, assuming the physical form &amp; sensations it’s always craved by mingling with her blood, and the Dark Gift is born.<br>
<br>
Anyway, Akasha doesn’t require any of the empty ‘Gods’ or ‘Goddesses’ of her past, that have all let her down so badly.. she can become a ‘Goddess’ herself, ie. BE what she never could find..<br>
<br>
Well, it’s really well written &amp; Anne Rice novels are full of stuff like that (the main characters, many of them anyway, struggle with making sense of life, death, heaven &amp; hell etc etc.. actually, Anne Rices characters ~ the vampires~ say more about being human than any I’ve read anywhere.. like when Lestat ‘body switches’ &amp; becomes mortal for a period, but he’s lost sight completely of all the silly, messy practicalities of being human, like the fact that clothes aren’t just an adornment, you NEED them in the mddle of a harsh winter to avoid dying of pneumonia, you NEED to eat to live, you need to do lots of repetitive, tiresome, dumb things just to get by 24/7.. so he struggles hopelessly being ‘mortal’ again, and almost dies)<br>
<br>
Anyway, I’ve gone off on a BIGGG tangent now, and it’s late so I gotta go.<br>
<br>
See ya!!<br>
<br>
Towelfrood/ Paul<br>
