<br>
Weaving religious themage into writing is a good think in my humble opinion.  Though "The Lord of the Rings" are definitely secular fantasies, I find a lot of Christian themage in them, and I've read C.S. Lewis "Chronicles of Narnia" (save for the 5th and 7th books...argh..must get my paws on those, read them in high school and the library didn't have those two books of the series >_< !  )  <br>
<br>
And, I like to let my faith color my own writing.  I'm not preachy in my work (like the Left Behind authors are in theirs!), I just kind of use the symbolism and themage.  I think it makes books MUCH more interesting than leaving matters of faith and the human psyche out completely.  <br>
<br>
As for the original topic...um, the Inquisition was bad...but lots of diffrent faith groups have done atrocities in the name of their ideologies....it's not a faith thing, it's a human thing.  I don't see religion as the root of all human suffering and evil, I just think that large groups of humans like to use religion as a justification for doing bad things.  I mean, I don't see Muslims as a whole as evil people, though the terrorists who attacked the World Trade Center and the Pentagon were using their particular brand of Islam as a justification for their actions.  Yes, Christians and professed "Christians" have done lots of bad things in the name of God, but, lots of Mulisms have done bad things in the name of Allah, lots of Romans did bad things in the names of their gods, the Aztecs did bad things in the name of Quetzecoltyl  (Is the spelling right?  Aztec war-god)...<br>
<br>
yeah, and anywhere where too many people think alike and individual freedom is repressed...um...stand up to it....for I think getting too collective kinda breeds stuff like Inquisitions.  <br>
